Kara and Nate did mess up in not releasing the vlog and instead putting it with the documentary, and that did upset some people (including myself) and understandably so. It's saddening to see that this has resulted in hours of stress for both Kara and Nate, as well as forced them to make the documentary completely free AND release it earlier than planned.

snippet.textDisplay: So I don't think that what they did was wrong but I can understand the outrage.  These two are two of the kindest down to earth people on youtube, almost to a fault, and that takes us to this point.  I can understand how people feel betrayed because Kara and Nate never ask for money in their videos or overburden you with sponsorship's, yes they do plug products and their own products but don't shove it down your throat like other youtubers do and if they do they give you a warning and they have never done anything to restrict a video from their viewers.  That being said I feel some people have been chomping at the bit waiting for the hundredth country video a lot longer than we have usually do, with no real explanation as to why like we have in the past with other prolonged video waits (like when they are in another country with limited access) this wait seemed to have no explanation and then all of a sudden we get a video saying the 100th country and get slapped with a paywall.  I think mostly it was a knee-jerk reaction to something so sudden and unexpected from this couple to suddenly have such a long awaited video was suddenly restricted by a paywall, even if it was just a minimum of a dollar,  with no real warning this was happening, especially with the 100th county video attached to the end of the documentary it felt like a slap in the face and felt more like "Hey thank you for watching us for several years and getting us to our 100th country, now give us money to see the video you have been waiting for for years."  I think what hit people most was all the build up to the 100th country with hyping it up having viewers vote on it and just dangling this big milestone under everyone's nose to just suddenly put a paywall in front of it(yes i know it would have been put on you tube for free later in the month but its still hurts a little to think that all of a sudden money was suddenly a factor when it hasn't been in the past) The cool think about Kara and Nate is they feel like real people who are not in it just for the money, and a paywall even as cheap as it was still hurt some because some creators who use paywalls tend to care just about the money. I think if they would have made this announcement earlier before posting it behind the paywall it might have gone over better had people known what was going to happen but the fact that this couple who has never asked anything of their content and have always made it accessible to everyone are suddenly asking you to pay for a milestone video everyone has been waiting for with no warning to people by surprise.  I am coming to this in the aftermath because i was not able to watch the first video or see the original comments when it came out so i had to catch up, but Nate nailed it with the apology even though i don't think it should have gotten that far and am disappointed that this project they worked so hard on is getting the credit it deserves taken away from it from the forced refunds.  If you made it this far I commend you I realize i got long winded but I wanted to put in my opinion, I hope this experience does not discourage Kara and Nate from continuing this journey and that they learn and move on from this experience and continue to bring us along on their journeys.
